website_summaries.verdict: While not ideal for most motorists, it tops the pack for high-powered engines and race car enthusiasts.
pros: Raises fuel octane levels up to 105, making it an ideal choice for racing, 2 stroke, and E85 engines
cons: Contains MMT – may cause clogs in fuel injectors or spark plugs with extended use
Known to cause damage to paint if leaked or spilled on it
Lack of long spout makes it challenging to use without spilling

customer_reviews.title: Why so much?
customer_reviews.text: To turn 93 octane gas into 98-99, which is ideal for my car, I have to use the entire 32 oz bottle. For Boostane, I only have to use 0.15 of a 32oz bottle. Race gas is also much more expensive per 32 oz bottle too. Boostane also has additives to stabilize the mixture. Race gas doesn't.
customer_reviews.author: Tom S

customer_reviews.title: I prefer it over actual race gas
customer_reviews.text: Just dyno-tested a 1000+hp twin-turbo big block and instead of buying race gas I started with 5 gallons of 92 plus the concentrate, which yielded 104 octane per the mixing instructions. Never encountered detonation. Smelled like the real deal when we have a fuel leak even! In some ways I prefer it to race gas from a drum because you never really know how fresh that stuff is, particularly at the start/end of a season. With the concentrate you're using local supply that's likely always fresh.
customer_reviews.author: Davepl

customer_reviews.title: Boosted octane=Performance
customer_reviews.text: I was looking for something to help me boost the octane to 100 and this did the job. I have a 2004 supercharged Lightning and i have a tune with lots of parts and with 93 octane it would ping and knock some times, but i installed the whole 32 oz can to 10 gallons of 93 and it got me 99.5 about . Big difference. No more pinging or knocking and it has allowed the tune to perform to its fullest. Nice....If you're running a boosted engine give it a try. Don't waste your money buying others. This works.
customer_reviews.author: scott
